{"id":"2303.14057","submitter":"Clifford Smyth","authors":"David Galvin, John Engbers, Clifford Smyth","title":"Reciprocals of thinned exponential series","comments":"34 pages, revised, a new section 6 proves the main result in an\n  alternative way using the Run Theorem","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math.CA","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The reciprocal of $e^{-x}$ has a power series about $0$ in which all\ncoefficients are non-negative. Gessel [Reciprocals of exponential polynomials\nand permutation enumeration, Australas. J. Combin., 74, 2019] considered\ntruncates of the power series of $e^{-x}$, i.e. polynomials of the form\n$\\sum_{n=0}^r (-1)^n\\frac{x^n}{n!}$, and established combinatorially that the\nreciprocal of the truncate has a power series with all coefficients\nnon-negative precisely when $r$ is odd.\n  Here we extend Gessel's observations to arbitrary ``thinned exponential\nseries''.\n  To be precise, let $A \\subseteq \\{1,3,5,\\ldots\\}$ and $B \\subseteq\n\\{2,4,6,\\ldots\\}$, and consider the series\n  \\[\n  1-\\sum_{a \\in A} \\frac{x^a}{a!} + \\sum_{b \\in B} \\frac{x^b}{b!}.\n  \\]\n  We consider conditions on $A$ and $B$ that ensure that the reciprocal series\nhas all coefficients non-negative. We give combinatorial proofs for a large set\nof conditions, including whenever $1 \\in A$ and the endpoints of the maximal\nconsecutive intervals in $A \\cup B$ are odd integers.\n  In particular, the coefficients in the reciprocal series can be interpreted\nas ordered set partitions of $[n]$ with block size restrictions, or in terms of\npermutations with restricted lengths of maximally increasing runs, suitably\nweighted.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 24 Mar 2023 15:08:39 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Wed, 24 May 2023 11:58:38 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-25"}
