{"id":"2303.14064","submitter":"Henrique De Andrade Gomes","authors":"Henrique Gomes and Carlo Rovelli","title":"On the analogies between gravitational and electromagnetic radiative\n  energy","comments":"16 pages, 6 page appendix","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.hist-ph gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We give a conceptual exposition of aspects of gravitational radiation,\nespecially in relation to energy. Our motive for doing so is that the strong\nanalogies with electromagnetic radiation seem not to be widely enough\nappreciated. In particular, we reply to some recent papers in the philosophy of\nphysics literature that seem to deny that gravitational waves carry energy.\n  Our argument is based on two points: (i) that for both electromagnetism and\ngravity, in the presence of material sources, radiation is an effective\nconcept, unambiguously emerging only in certain regimes or solutions of the\ntheory; and (ii) similarly, energy conservation is only unambiguous in certain\nregimes or solutions of general relativity. Crucially, the domain of (i), in\nwhich radiation is meaningful, has a significant overlap with the domain of\n(ii), in which energy conservation is meaningful. Conceptually, the overlap of\nregimes is no coincidence: the long-standing question about the existence of\ngravitational waves was settled precisely by finding a consistent way to\narticulate their energy and momentum.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 24 Mar 2023 15:20:12 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-03-27"}
